In Raman scattering, the Stokes-shifted scattered photon loses an energy quantum equal to the vibrational energy of the active mode. Using energy conservation in wavenumber form,
$$h c 	ilde{
u}_{S} = h c 	ilde{
u}_{0} - h c 	ilde{
u}_{	ext{vib}},$$
where $	ilde{
u}_{0} =  rac{1}{\lambda}$ is the incident wavenumber, $	ilde{
u}_{S}$ is the scattered wavenumber, and $	ilde{
u}_{	ext{vib}}$ is the vibrational wavenumber of the mode. Dividing by $h c$ gives
$$	ilde{
u}_{S} = 	ilde{
u}_{0} - 	ilde{
u}_{	ext{vib}}.$$
The Raman shift is defined as
$$\Delta 	ilde{
u} \equiv 	ilde{
u}_{0} - 	ilde{
u}_{S}.$$
Substituting the expression for $	ilde{
u}_{S}$,
$$\Delta 	ilde{
u} = 	ilde{
u}_{0} - \left(	ilde{
u}_{0} - 	ilde{
u}_{	ext{vib}}ight) = 	ilde{
u}_{	ext{vib}}.$$
Therefore, the Raman shift equals the vibrational wavenumber of the mode and is independent of the excitation wavelength. For two different lasers with wavelengths $\lambda_{1}$ and $\lambda_{2}$,
$$\Delta 	ilde{
u}_{1} = 	ilde{
u}_{	ext{vib}} = \Delta 	ilde{
u}_{2}.$$
Given that $\Delta 	ilde{
u}_{1} = 459 	ext{ cm}^{-1}$ for the symmetric stretch, the expected shift with the UV laser is the same, $\Delta 	ilde{
u}_{2} = 459 	ext{ cm}^{-1}$. The correct choice is A.
